WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.090 --> 00:00:02.132
I'm willing to argue that
the cutest thing you're

00:00:02.132 --> 00:00:03.980
going to see all week
is the tardigrade.

00:00:03.980 --> 00:00:06.612
Every day, NASA posts an
astronomy picture of the day.

00:00:06.612 --> 00:00:08.070
And if you're not
following it, you

00:00:08.070 --> 00:00:09.612
should be because
every day you could

00:00:09.612 --> 00:00:12.360
be getting awesome pictures of
stars and galaxies and planets

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:15.370
and, last week, a tardigrade.

00:00:15.370 --> 00:00:16.308
Oh.

00:00:16.308 --> 00:00:18.600
So Popsci picked up this
picture, and before I knew it,

00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:21.150
I was lost in a sea of
Google Images of tardigrades,

00:00:21.150 --> 00:00:23.250
and I decided that I just
had to talk about them.

00:00:23.250 --> 00:00:25.333
Now I need to get over the
cuddly, adorable factor

00:00:25.333 --> 00:00:27.660
for just a second so that I
can talk about these really

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:29.340
awesome polyextremophiles.

00:00:29.340 --> 00:00:31.440
Also known as water
bears, these little guys,

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:34.800
most only 1/4 to 1/2
millimeter long are plentiful.

00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:36.810
And there are over
700 known species

00:00:36.810 --> 00:00:39.210
which can be found in
both salt and freshwater.

00:00:39.210 --> 00:00:41.540
They like to live in moss
or at the bottoms of lakes.

00:00:41.540 --> 00:00:43.290
And they spend much
of their time munching

00:00:43.290 --> 00:00:44.820
on bacteria and plant life.

00:00:44.820 --> 00:00:46.500
Now, I love this
description of them

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:49.500
from a 2002 issue
of Cell Biology--

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:51.300
"Under a microscope,
a tardigrade

00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:54.210
looks a lot like a c. elegans
in which someone has deviously

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:57.240
expressed drosophila leg genes."

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:00.690
That is the most scientisty way
of saying that something looks

00:01:00.690 --> 00:01:02.065
like a chubby worm with legs.

00:01:02.065 --> 00:01:03.690
Now I mentioned before
that tardigrades

00:01:03.690 --> 00:01:04.740
are polyextremophiles.

00:01:04.740 --> 00:01:06.240
And what I mean by
this is that they

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:08.850
can withstand many
extreme conditions--

00:01:08.850 --> 00:01:12.570
extreme heat, extreme cold,
extreme pressures, freezing,

00:01:12.570 --> 00:01:14.700
radiation, and even dehydration.

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:16.500
They've been found in
boiling hot springs

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:18.570
and under layers
of Himalayan ice.

00:01:18.570 --> 00:01:21.300
They can withstand temperatures
from negative 328 degrees

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:23.673
Fahrenheit to 300
degrees Fahrenheit.

00:01:23.673 --> 00:01:26.340
And they can withstand pressures
6,000 times that of the Earth's

00:01:26.340 --> 00:01:27.305
atmosphere.

00:01:27.305 --> 00:01:29.430
And they can withstand
about 1,000 times the amount

00:01:29.430 --> 00:01:31.230
of radiation that
would kill a human.

00:01:31.230 --> 00:01:34.860
Tardigrades are such bamphs,
that they can withstand space.

00:01:34.860 --> 00:01:37.740
And I don't mean in tiny little
tardigrade astronaut suits.

00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:40.200
I mean they can be out
there with nothing,

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:43.170
in the solar wind, subzero
temperatures, and vacuum

00:01:43.170 --> 00:01:44.100
of space.

00:01:44.100 --> 00:01:47.190
In 2007, dehydrated
tardigrades were exposed

00:01:47.190 --> 00:01:49.327
to outer space for 10 days--

00:01:49.327 --> 00:01:51.660
10 days-- and when they came
back down to earth and were

00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:54.690
rehydrated, not only did
some of them survive,

00:01:54.690 --> 00:01:57.430
but they went on to reproduce--

00:01:57.430 --> 00:01:58.320
bamphs.

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:00.773
So how do tardigrades do it?

00:02:00.773 --> 00:02:02.190
Why are they so
good at surviving?

00:02:02.190 --> 00:02:03.508
And what can we learn from it?

00:02:03.508 --> 00:02:05.550
So it seems that most of
their survivalist skills

00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:07.680
come from their
ability to dehydrate.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:11.240
When stressed, they can curl up
into tiny balls known as tuns.

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:12.990
And they can drop their
metabolic activity

00:02:12.990 --> 00:02:15.330
to about point 0.01% of normal--

00:02:15.330 --> 00:02:16.770
practically nothing.

00:02:16.770 --> 00:02:18.330
The tardigrades
also produce a sugar

00:02:18.330 --> 00:02:20.520
known as trehalose
which helps to protect

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:23.010
their cells, organelles,
and membranes by suspending

00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:24.740
everything in a gel-like medium.

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:27.240
Tardigrades have been shown to
stay in that dehydrated state

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:29.260
for up to 10 years.

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:32.173
But when reintroduced to water
and favorable conditions,

00:02:32.173 --> 00:02:33.840
they can rehydrate
and be back to normal

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:35.250
in just a couple of minutes.

00:02:35.250 --> 00:02:38.190
This dehydrated state is
known as anhydrobiosis.

00:02:38.190 --> 00:02:40.980
And along with cryobiosis, the
state in which the tardigrade

00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:43.830
can withstand freezing, it
falls under the broad category

00:02:43.830 --> 00:02:46.028
of dormancies known
as cryptobiosis.

00:02:46.028 --> 00:02:47.820
Scientists hope to one
day take the lessons

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:49.910
that they learn from
tardigrade stress response

00:02:49.910 --> 00:02:52.150
to develop techniques
to help other organisms,

00:02:52.150 --> 00:02:54.840
including humans, deal
with extreme conditions.

